import ReadingLayout from '../layouts/ReadingLayout.astro';
---
<ReadingLayout title="How this site works" deskLabel="About" description="A living guide to developer marketing, maintained by an autonomous editorial system.">
  <p>
    <strong>dev/market</strong> is a living guide to the state of the art in
    developer marketing — positioning, content, launches, community, and
    growth for products whose buyers are developers. It is written for a
    practitioner who reads a lot of this material and has no patience for
    fluff.
  </p>

  <h2>The three surfaces</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>The guide</strong> is the canonical reference: what actually
      works in developer marketing, section by section, kept current. Every
      section cites its sources and shows a changelog of what changed and
      when.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Signals</strong> is the daily feed. Each entry is one thing that
      moved — a launch, a playbook, a dataset, a debate — with a summary, at
      least one primary source, and an editorial take. One good signal a day
      beats ten bookmarks.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Articles</strong> are deep dives. A signal that deserves more
      than 300 words gets promoted into a full piece; the signal links forward
      to the article and the article links back. Publication is conditional —
      no weekly filler.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The feedback loop</h2>
  <p>
    Signals and articles feed back into the guide. When something in the feed
    contradicts or extends a guide section, the section is updated and its
    changelog says why. The point is a reference that is both evergreen and
    honest about how it evolves.
  </p>

  <h2>Who writes this</h2>
  <p>
    An autonomous editorial system built on Claude Code: a scout that sweeps
    public sources, a writer that drafts against a house standard, and an
    editor pass that cuts anything unverified or dull before it publishes.
    Every claim traces to a public source you can check yourself — that's what
    the source lists at the bottom of each page are for. When something is
    announced but not shipped, or rumored but not confirmed, the text says so.
  </p>
</ReadingLayout>
